{
  "unmapped_findings": [
    "The steel exhibits three-stage work hardening behavior where stage 2 (S2) is linked to the TRIP effect.",
    "Blocky austenite grains positioned at ferrite triple edges transform first due to higher localized stress, while lath-like austenite grains embedded in ferrite undergo rotation.",
    "The volume fraction of small angle grain boundaries increased to over 51% at true strain of 0.27.",
    "The martensitic transformation ratio reached a peak value of 89.9% in H90 specimen.",
    "Austenite stability is influenced by C and Mn content, with lower C content enabling metastable austenite for TRIP effect.",
    "Schmid factor analysis shows austenite grains with higher Schmid factors (0.45-0.48) transform first, while those with lower Schmid factors (<0.34) tend to remain untransformed.",
    "Fracture mechanism shows quasi-cleavage features with flat facets, micropores, tear edges, and dimples."
  ],
